During 1983, the Administrative Office of the U.S. Courts, with the support of the Federal Probation Division, began compiling a comprehensive offenderbased data file about sentencing practices. Known as FPSSIS (Federal Probation Sentencing and Supervision Information System), these data provided information about most felony and serious misdemeanor cases leading to convictions since the middle of 1983. FPSSIS is a rich source of information that includes a description of the offense, a characterization of the offender’s background and criminal record, whether the offender was convicted by guilty plea or trial, and the sentence received.
FPSSIS formed the core of the commission’scurrentpractices data, but it was necessary to augment the file for two reasons. First, FPSSIS did not include somevariables that were deemedrelevant to guideline-basedsentencing. Second, it allowed only very rough estimates of time served by convicted offenders. The impact model required precise estimates of time served for the narrow offense and offender categories stipulated by the guidelines, and FPSSIS was unable to satisfy that need.
To enrich the FPSSIS data, thereby solving the first problem, the commission drew a sample from the 40,000 defendants convicted during fiscal year 1985 (October 1,1984-Septemkr 30,1985).This sample consistedof 11,OOO defendants and represented a diverse cross-section of the-federaloffender population; included were casesfor streetcrime, white-collaroffenses,drugoffenses,and otherfederal crimes. The commission developed a detailed data collection form expanding on characteristics of the offense and offender, and had the Probation Division of the Administrative Office complete the form for the 11,OOO cases.
The Probation Division provided 10,500 responses in addition to the corresponding presentence investigation repork, thus giving the commission quantitative information in the form of 10,500 computer records and qualitative information in the form of 10,500 presentence reports.
In response to the second problem, data from the Bureau of Prisons and the Parole Commission were added to FPSSIS, enabling the commission accurately to estimate time served by convicted offenders. For each of the 10,500 records, the Bureau of Prisons specified one of the following: the length of time the offenderserved in prison; the length of time the offender was scheduled to serve in prison if a parole date had been set; or the length of time the offender was expected to remain in prison accordingto rules that the bureau routinelyemploys to estimate release dates. When the bureau could not provide estimates, the commission relied on computerizedParole Commissionrecords and, when these were unavailable, estimates of time served based on an analysis of prevailing release practices.
The FPSSIS data were too recent to provide adequateinformationaboutcurrent probation and parole supervision practices and time served following a parole revocation. For this information, the commission relied on two sources: extant tabulations and commission-conductedstatistical analyses based on supervision

