This preliminary discussion notwithstanding, there are significantobstacles to projecting prison impact based on a simple comparison between current sentencing practices and the guidelines. Such a comparison provides no information about the number of offenders who will be sentenced for specific crimes, and requires an assumption that the extremely long sentences for certain defendants-drug dealers, career offenders, and violent criminals-will be applied in full, an Occurrence that is unlikely in the face of significant incentives to plea bargain. The methodology applied in the commission’s prison impact model overcomes these and other obstacles.

METHODOLOGY
To estimate prison impact, it is necessary to project future prison demands in the absence of guidelines,thereby establishinga “baseline.”This already formidable task is complicated by two new laws, both of which are expected to increase the frequency and duration of prison terms. The Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986 raised the minimum and maximum prison terms for most convicted drug dealers; the career offender provision of the Crime Control Act of 1984 required lengthened prison time for certain repeat offenders. Both laws had to be incorporated into the guidelines, but it would be misleading to attribute the effect of their provisions to the guidelines themselves. Thus it was necessary to compare incarceration under the guidelines with a baseline projection based on the cumulative effect

