Current Sentencing Practices
As discussed earlier, we had detailed information about federal offenders who were sentenced during fiscal year 1985. To develop the baseline, we made two fundamental assumptions. First, within an offense category-like bank robbery-offenders and offenses observed during 1985 mirror offenders and offenses that would be observed after 1985. For example, if half the robbers used guns during 1985, half would use guns during 1990, half during 1995, and so on. Second, in the absence of guidelines, sentences imposed and time served by 1985 defendants are indicative of sentences and time that would be served by future offenders with similar offense and offender characteristics. As an example, if during 1985 embezzlers who stole $500,000 served 12 months in prison, we assumed that during 1990 (absent guidelines) embezzlers who steal a similar amount would serve the same length of time.

Conviction Trends
One obvious factor that influences any prison population forecast is the future level of crime. Except for short-term projections, however, no reliable method exists for predicting future federal crime rates. Even if future crime rates could be predicted with an acceptable degree of accuracy, historical data indicate a very weak relationship between changes in the number of offenses of a given type and changes in the contemporaneous level of federal prosecutions. Such discrepancies result partially from the exercise of discretion by U.S. attorneys, who may refer cases to state or local authorities, or simply decline prosecution for policy r e a ~ o n s . ~
Discrepancies between changes in specific crime rates and prosecutions may also arise because of altered enforcement priorities. To the extent that these priorities are set by the administration in office, predicting future priorities involves predicting the outcomes of future elections and the policies pursued by successive administrations.
Rather than speculate about the future political climate, we adopted two diffenmt assumptionsregarding futureprosecutions. One presumes “low-growth” in prosecutions and the other “high growth.” In the low-growth projections, we assumed that the average year-by-year increase from 1982 through 1986 would continue only through 1989. This assumption reflects the fact that the present administration, whose policies determined the growth pattern for 1982 through 1986, will have

