Drug Law
The Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986 greatly increased most of the punishments for violating the nation's drug laws and extended the laws to cover some special situations. Because implementation of the drug law coincided with development of the impact model, we were unable to rely on actual observations to determine how the drug law would influence the baseline. We were forced instead to simulate sentencing under the new drug law.
The Anti-Drug Abuse Act stipulates minimum and maximum terms based on the amount of drugs involved in the offender's crime. Because drug amount was included in the 1985 cohort data, we used it to determine the minimum and maximum terms "at risk," that is, the shortest and longest sentences that could be served based on the drug amount. The basic approach was to compare time actually served by members of the 1985 cohort to the minimum and maximum terms required by the new drug law. When the defendant served less than the new drug law minimum, the computer model assumed that he would have served the minimum had the new drug law been applicableat the time he was sentenced. (The drug law increased maximum terms, so no defendants sentenced prior to the drug law served more time that the drug law maximums.) Otherwise, the model assumed that under the drug law he would serve exactly the sentence that
he served according to the FPSSIS data.
This basic approach was modified in two regards. First, we assumed that the minimum terms would not constrain plea bargaining; specifically, we assumed that a defendant could negotiate for a sentence reduction that would be equivalent (in terms of percentage reduction in time served) to the sentence reduction that was typical for the 1985 cohort. Second, the Anti-Drug Abuse Act puts no constraints on sentences when the defendant cooperates with authorities, so in such cases (as identified in the 1985 data) we assumed that time served would be equivalent to what it was during 1985.
