Career Offender Provision

Inclusion of the career offender provision was straightforward. The Crime Control Act of 1984 required the commission to set prison terms for certain repeat offenders (those convicted of violent crimes and selling drugs who had two or more prior convictions for similar crimes) “at or near the maximum term authorized [by law].” Thus the basic approach was to determine the minimum sentence required and the maximum sentence allowed by the guidelines, and then assume that the defendant would be sentenced to the minimum if his actual time was less than the minimum, to the maximum if his actual time was greater than the maximum, and to his actual time otherwise. These results were adjusted for plea-bargain concessions, using the same assumptions that were employed for drug cases.

Sentences Under the Guidelines
The next step was the “heart” of the impact analysis. To assess the impact of the guidelines on the federal prison population, the simulation“resentences”each member of the 1985 cohort using the guidelines’ provisions. Each offender’s data was examined to determine his conviction offense, his criminal history, and other circumstances of his crime to assess the sentence he was “at risk” of receiving under the guidelines. The guidelines prescribe a sentence range, so the at-risk maximum was the top of the range and the at-risk minimum was the bottom of the range.
The at-risk sentence was reduced by a specific percentage (depending on the offense type) when the defendant entered a guilty plea. These percentage reductions were determined from analyses of current plea negotiation practices. The at-risk sentence was reduced to the amount of time actually served by the 1985 cohort member when there was substantial cooperation with the government. We assumed that probation would be the guidelines sentence when the guidelines allowed probation as a choice (after the plea-bargain concession) and the 1985 cohort member had actually received probation. Otherwise, we assumed that the defendant would serve the midpoint of the guideline range, minus 15% when allowed by good-time provisions.

Delay in Application of the Guidelines
Not everyone convicted after November 1, 1987, will be sentenced under the guidelines. To be subject to the guidelines, the defendant must have been convicted of a crime that was committed afer November 1 . When we projected the 1985 cohort forward, we also projected forward the date that the defendants committed their crimes, and we simulated an application of the guidelines only when the projected crime commission date was later than November 1, 1987.

