Sensitivity Analysis
Accuracy when measuring the effect of major changes was of utmost importance to the commission, but the projections were carried out in the presence of many imponderables. Because guideline-induced charges are likely to be substantial, and because future reaction by federaljudges and others is unknown, we modified the simulation to accommodate several alternative scenarios.
We modified the basic scenario, discussed above, in three ways. First, as discussed earlier, we adopted alternative low- and high-growth paths, and compared projections for each. Second, we had to predict judicial reactions to the guidelines. Basically, we assumed that judges would depart infrequentlyfrom the guidelines. However, the reasonableness of this assumption is arguable, so we adopted alternatives that simulated various degrees of departure. Thud, we had to model plea negotiations. The basic approach, as discussed already, was to assume that defendants will enter guilty pleas under the guidelines at the same rate as now, and that the percentage sentence reduction now exchanged for guilty pleas will approximate the reductions to occur in the future. Different assumptions, some of which allow greater sentence concessions and some of which allow lesser concessions, were introduced into the model. In total, prison population forecasts were derived for almost 20 different possible scenarios. The results under these various scenarios provide upper and lower bounds on the estimate of prison impact.

