The guidelines create two new types of sentences similar in form to a split sentence. For minimum sentences of no more than 6 months, the defendant may receive a term of probation that includes a period of intermittent or community confinement. For minimum sentencesof no morethan 10months, the defendant’s sentence may be “split” between incarceration and community confinement.
As Table 1 indicates, under the guidelines straight probation will be reduced. Currently 42.4% of all convicted defendants receive straight probation. After the guidelines are implemented,only 18.9% are projected to receive this sentence. For some crimes, the impact is even more dramatic. For example, while in income taxes cases, 57% of persons convicted of tax evasion presently receive probation, this is projected to fall to 13% under the guideline.
The guidelines were designed to reduce the disparity in sentencing as well as increase the effectivenessof the sentencing process. Hence the guidelines decrease the proportion of defendants who receive sentences that do not include any confinement and eliminate disparately long prison terms. We project that the certainty of confinement will be dramatically increased under the guidelines.
